Panthera pardus tulliana, also known as the Anatolian leopard or Persian leopard, is a leopard subspecies native to the Caucasus, Southern Russia, Iran, Turkmenistan, Afghanistan and Turkey. As of 2016, it has been listed as Endangered on the IUCN Red List, as fewer than 871â€“1,290 mature individuals were estimated to survive, with a declining trend.A phylogenetic analysis indicates that P. p. tulliana matrilineally belongs to a monophyletic group that diverged from the African (P. p. pardus) and the Arabian leopard (P. p. nimr) in the second half of the Pleistocene.

